ion:\n    def reversePairs(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve the problem of counting reverse pairs in an array efficiently, we can use a modified merge sort algorithm. This approach leverages the divide-and-conquer strategy to count the reverse pairs while sorting the array. The key idea is to count the reverse pairs during the merge step.\n\nHere's the complete solution:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def reversePairs(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        def merge_and_count(nums, start, mid, end):\n            count = 0\n            left = nums[start:mid]\n            right = nums[mid:end]\n            i = j = 0\n            k = start\n            \n            # Count reverse pairs\n            while i < len(left) and j < len(right):\n                if left[i] > 2 * right[j]:\n                    count += (mid - start) - i\n                    j += 1\n                else:\n                    i += 1\n            \n            # Merge the arrays\n            i = 0\n            j = 0\n            while i < len(left) and j < len(right):\n                if left[i] <= right[j]:\n                    nums[k] = left[i]\n                    i += 1\n                else:\n                    nums[k] = right[j]\n                    j += 1\n                k += 1\n            \n            while i < len(left):\n                nums[k] = left[i]\n                i += 1\n                k += 1\n            \n            while j < len(right):\n                nums[k] = right[j]\n                j += 1\n                k += 1\n            \n            return count\n        \n        def merge_sort_and_count(nums, start, end):\n            if end - start <= 1:\n                return 0\n            mid = (start + end) // 2\n            count = 0\n            count += merge_sort_and_count(nums, start, mid)\n            count += merge_sort_and_count(nums, mid, end)\n            count += merge_and_count(nums, start, mid, end)\n            return count\n        \n        return merge_sort_and_count(nums, 0, len(nums))\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Merge and Count**: This function takes two sorted halves of the array and counts the reverse pairs. It iterates through the left and right halves to count pairs where an element in the left half is greater than twice the element in the right half.\n   \n2. **Merge**: After counting, it merges the two halves into a single sorted array.\n\n3. **Merge Sort and Count**: This function recursively divides the array into halves, counts the reverse pairs in each half, and counts the reverse pairs across the halves using the `merge_and_count` function.\n\nThis approach ensures that we count the reverse pairs in `O(n log n)` time, which is efficient for the given constraints.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}